<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1311,1840]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
This genus is distributed in Asia from 
<collectingCountry box="[581,638,1311,1336]" name="India" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">India</collectingCountry>
to the 
<collectingCountry box="[716,842,1311,1336]" name="Philippines" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Philippines</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Polhemus" box="[857,1178,1311,1336]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" refString="Polhemus, J. T. &amp; Andersen, N. M. (1984) A revision of Amemboa Esaki with notes on the phylogeny and ecological evolution of eotrechine water striders (Insecta, Hemiptera, Gerridae). Steenstrupia, 10, 65 - 111." type="journal article" year="1984">
Polhemus &amp; Andersen 
<number box="[1119,1178,1312,1336]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="1984.0">1984</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, Zettel et al. 
<number box="[1323,1381,1312,1336]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="2007.0">2007</number>
) and was revised by 
<bibRefCitation author="Polhemus" box="[324,678,1348,1373]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" refString="Polhemus, J. T. &amp; Andersen, N. M. (1984) A revision of Amemboa Esaki with notes on the phylogeny and ecological evolution of eotrechine water striders (Insecta, Hemiptera, Gerridae). Steenstrupia, 10, 65 - 111." type="journal article" year="1984">
Polhemus and Andersen (
<number box="[611,669,1348,1372]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="1984.0">1984</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
with a key for 
<number box="[848,876,1348,1372]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="23.0">23</number>
species requiring male specimens. Later, 
<number box="[1345,1372,1348,1372]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="11.0">11</number>
more species were described from Southeast Asia (
<bibRefCitation author="Zettel" box="[678,815,1383,1408]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" refString="Zettel, H. (1995) Two new Amemboa Esaki, 1925 from Borneo and Vietnam. Annales Historico-Naturales Musei Nationalis Hungarici, 87, 63 - 66." type="journal article" year="1995">
Zettel 
<number box="[756,815,1383,1408]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="1995.1998">1995</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, 1998, 
<number box="[903,962,1384,1408]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="2002.0">2002</number>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Zettel" box="[977,1214,1383,1408]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" refString="Zettel, H. &amp; Chen, P. - P. (1996) Beitrag zur Taxonomie und Faunistik der Gerridae Vietnams mit Neubeschreibungen der Gattung Andersenius gen. nov. aus der Unteramilie Ptilomerinae und weiterer Arten (Insecta: Heteroptera: Gerridae). Entomologische Abhandlungen des Museums fur Tierkunde Dresden, 57, 149 - 182." type="journal article" year="1996">
Zettel &amp; Chen 
<number box="[1155,1214,1383,1408]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="1996.1997">1996</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Zettel" box="[1228,1287,1384,1408]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" refString="Zettel, H. &amp; Chen, P. - P. (1997) Three new taxa of Amemboa ESAKI, 1925, from Thailand and Vietnam. Annales Historico- Naturales Musei Nationalis Hungarici, 89, 93 - 101." type="journal article" year="1997">1997</bibRefCitation>
; Zettel et al. 
<number box="[151,212,1420,1444]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="2007.0">2007</number>
). Including two species reported here from 
<collectingCountry box="[721,821,1420,1445]" name="Thailand" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Thailand</collectingCountry>
for the first time, the 
<collectingCountry box="[1084,1135,1420,1445]" name="Thailand" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Thai</collectingCountry>
fauna contains 
<number box="[1322,1350,1420,1445]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="15.0">15</number>
known species of 
<emphasis box="[271,390,1455,1480]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">
<taxonomicName box="[271,386,1455,1480]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Amemboa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Amemboa</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
more than that of any other country in Indochina (Zettel 
<number box="[1045,1104,1455,1480]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="1996.0">1996</number>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Chen" box="[1116,1358,1455,1480]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" refString="Chen, P. - P. &amp; Zettel, H. (1998) Key to genera and subgenera of Gerridae (Gerromorpha) of Thailand and adjacent countries, with a check-list of species known from Thailand. Amemboa, 2, 24 - 41." type="journal article" year="1998" yearSuffix="a">
Chen &amp; Zettel 
<number box="[1287,1345,1456,1480]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="1998.0">1998</number>
a
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Zettel" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" refString="Zettel, H. (2002) Description of Amemboa heissi sp. n. (Heteroptera: Gerridae) from south Thailand. Linzer Biologische Beitraege, 34, 1531 - 1534." type="journal article" year="2002">
Zettel 
<number box="[151,210,1492,1516]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Vitheepradit" box="[220,426,1492,1517]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" refString="Vitheepradit, A. (2008) The semiaquatic Heteroptera (Gerromorpha) of Thailand: Faunistics, Biogeography, and Phylogeography. Ph. D. Dissertation, University of Missouri, Columbia, Missouri, USA. [total page number not cited]" type="book" year="2008">
Vitheepradit 
<number box="[365,426,1492,1516]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="2008.0">2008</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Mostly, members of this genus in 
<collectingCountry box="[819,919,1492,1517]" name="Thailand" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Thailand</collectingCountry>
are found resting at the margins of rock pools, puddles, and streams. Moreover, they are one of few gerromorphans that are found in temporary mud puddles in 
<collectingCountry box="[151,254,1564,1589]" name="Thailand" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Thailand</collectingCountry>
. When they are pursued, they usually jump further onto the water surface to escape (
<bibRefCitation author="Polhemus" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" refString="Polhemus, J. T. &amp; Andersen, N. M. (1984) A revision of Amemboa Esaki with notes on the phylogeny and ecological evolution of eotrechine water striders (Insecta, Hemiptera, Gerridae). Steenstrupia, 10, 65 - 111." type="journal article" year="1984">
Polhemus &amp; Andersen 
<number box="[266,326,1600,1624]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="1984.0">1984</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). The genus is represented by two subgenera, 
<taxonomicName box="[851,963,1599,1624]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Amemboa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[851,963,1599,1624]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Amemboa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[1020,1163,1599,1624]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Amemboides</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Polhemus" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" refString="Polhemus, J. T. &amp; Andersen, N. M. (1984) A revision of Amemboa Esaki with notes on the phylogeny and ecological evolution of eotrechine water striders (Insecta, Hemiptera, Gerridae). Steenstrupia, 10, 65 - 111." type="journal article" year="1984">
Polhemus &amp; Andersen 
<number box="[151,211,1636,1660]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="1984.0">1984</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Members of the subgenus 
<taxonomicName box="[531,643,1636,1661]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Amemboa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[531,643,1636,1661]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Amemboa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have the first segment of the middle tarsus about twice as long as the second segment, whereas members of subgenus 
<emphasis box="[706,849,1671,1696]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Amemboides</emphasis>
have the first segment distinctly less than twice as long as the second segment (
<bibRefCitation author="Polhemus" box="[475,799,1708,1733]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" refString="Polhemus, J. T. &amp; Andersen, N. M. (1984) A revision of Amemboa Esaki with notes on the phylogeny and ecological evolution of eotrechine water striders (Insecta, Hemiptera, Gerridae). Steenstrupia, 10, 65 - 111." type="journal article" year="1984">
Polhemus &amp; Andersen 
<number box="[739,799,1708,1732]" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" value="1984.0">1984</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Six species of the subgenus 
<taxonomicName box="[1138,1250,1708,1733]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Amemboa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1138,1250,1708,1733]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Amemboa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and two species of the subgenus 
<emphasis box="[365,508,1743,1768]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Amemboides</emphasis>
were collected in the Phetchabun Mountains. Diagnoses are provided for comparisons among males only within each subgenus. 
<taxonomicName authority="Polhemus &amp; Andersen" authorityName="Polhemus &amp; Andersen" box="[776,1268,1780,1805]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Amemboa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="incurvata">
<emphasis box="[776,1004,1780,1805]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Amemboa incurvata</emphasis>
Polhemus &amp; Andersen
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Zettel" authorityName="Zettel" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Amemboa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laotica">
<emphasis box="[1325,1436,1780,1805]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">A. laotica</emphasis>
Zettel
</taxonomicName>
are reported from 
<collectingCountry box="[426,526,1815,1840]" name="Thailand" pageId="2" pageNumber="49">Thailand</collectingCountry>
for the first time.
</paragraph>
